<FONT CLASS="title16">Storing</FONT><BR> 

<font class="bodyCopySmall">
Refrigerators are dry and drafty. They rob your cheese of precious moisture. But unless you have a very cool, very moist home, the fridge is still your best bet for storing cheeses.
<P> 
<b>Wrapping</b><br>
We deliver your cheeses carefully wrapped in materials especially designed for cheese. Be sure to rewrap them diligently when putting them away (unless you polish off the entire order in one sitting, a distinct possibility). Saran Wrap or other plastic films are fine, but they can give your cheese a plasticky flavor. If you use plastic, be sure to rewrap frequently and use a new piece of film every time. Aluminum foil, lined butcher paper, or sturdy waxed paper is better for the cheese and keeps it just as fresh. 
<P> 
<b>Storing in the Refrigerator</b><br>
To minimize the drying ravages of the refrigerator, store your cheese in the least drafty part, such as a butter or vegetable drawer. Even better, create a humid little microclimate in your refrigerator by keeping your cheeses in a lidded terra-cotta pot, overturned flowerpot, or Tupperware box.
<P> 
<b>A Note on Mold</b> <br>
Mold will grow on the cut surface of any real cheese. Don't be scared. Cheese can't exist without mold. The blue in blue cheese is mold. The white rind of Brie is mold. Cheeses depend on mold to ripen. It won't harm you or the cheese. Just pare it off. 
<P> 
<b>Freezing Cheese</b><br>
Don't do it! The moisture in the cheese will freeze and crystallize, forever damaging the cheese's texture and flavor.
<br>
